flowRoot.flowPara: outline definition = 2D, oriented, contiguous and successive lines and arcs
2D = plan (O,x,y) with a reference frame orthonormal
oriented = from first point to last point
contiguous = the last point of a segment is the first point of the next segment
line = list of two points = first and last points of the line segement
arc = list of three points = first, middle (passing through) and last points of the arc segment
point = list of two floats = coordinates x and y of the point
The cnc_outline module helps to create and modify outlines.
If the last point is equal to the first point, the outline is closed. Otherwise the outline is open.
The orientation of a closed outline can be counter-clock-wise (CCW) or clock-wise (CW). This orientation should not have any consequence on the functions of the cnc_outline module.
An outline of n segments is defined by a list of (n+1) elements:
- the first element is the First point (or Start point)
- the second element is the first segement
- the (n+1) element is the last segment
A line segment is defined by its last point.
An arc segment is defined by a passing through point and its last point.
The first point of a line segment or an arc segment is not defined as it is the last point of the previous segement.
If the last point if the last segment is equal to the Start point, then the outline is closed.
The cnc_outline module uses two outline formats: with or without corner router_bit radius request.
outline format without corner router_bit request:
= coordinates x and y of the Start point
= coordinates x and y of the last point of the line segment
= coordinates x and y of the passing through point, followed by the coordinates x and y of the last point of the arc segment
In summary, this is a list of list of 2 or 4 floats. The first element of the global list is a list of 2 floats.
outline format with corner router_bit request:

- The corner router_bit radius request is a float. If the float is positive, the corner is requested to be smoothed with this radius. If the float is negative, the corner is requested to be enlarged with a radius equal to the absolute value of this float. If the float is equal to zero, the corner is requested to be unchanged and to keep its angular shape.
= coordinates x and y of the Start point and the requested radius of the Start point.
= coordinates x and y of the last point of the line segment and the requested radius of this last point.
= coordinates x and y of the passing through point, followed by the coordinates x and y of the last point of the arc segment and the requested radius of this last point.

If the outline is closed (ie the last point of the last segment is equal to the Start point), then the requested radius of last point must be set to zero as it has already been defined by the Start point.
If the outline is open, the request radius of the Start point and last point have no signification and should be set to zero.
In summary, this is a list of list of 3 or 5 floats. The first element of the global list is a list of 3 floats.
